{{Infobox person | name = Adolf Tobler | image = Nicola Perscheid - Adolf Tobler.jpg | alt = Photograph of Adolf Tobler, wearing spectacles and reading a book | caption = Adolf Tobler, photograph by [[Nicola Perscheid]] (1904) | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1835|05|24}} | birth_place = [[Hirzel]], Zürich, Switzerland | death_date = {{Death date and age|1910|03|18|1835|05|24}} | death_place = [[Berlin]], Germany | nationality = Swiss-German | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | relatives = [[Ludwig Tobler]] (brother) }}
'''Adolf Tobler''' (24 May 1835 &ndash; 18 March 1910) was a Swiss-German linguist and philologist. Born in [[Hirzel]] in Zürich, Switzerland, he was the brother of linguist [[Ludwig Tobler]] (1827–1895). Adolf Tobler died in [[Berlin]], Germany.
He studied [[Romance languages|Romance philology]] at the universities of [[University of Zürich|Zürich]] and [[University of Bonn|Bonn]], receiving his doctorate in 1857. At Bonn, he was influenced by the teachings of [[Friedrich Christian Diez]] and [[Nicolaus Delius]]. After graduation, he worked as a schoolteacher at the [[Solothurn (canton)|Solothurn]] cantonal school, then at the gymnasium in [[Bern]]. In 1867, he relocated to the [[University of Berlin]], where from 1871 up until his death, he held the chair of Romance philology. In 1890/91, he served as [[rector (academia)|university rector]].<ref name=HU>[https://www.hu-berlin.de/de/ueberblick/geschichte/rektoren/tobler Adolf Tobler] Humboldt-Universität zu Berlin (biography)</ref><ref>[http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D46328.php Tobler, Adolf] Historischen Lexikon der Schweiz</ref>
The "Tobler-Mussafia law", a grammatical rule applicable to Romance languages is named after Tobler and Austrian philologist [[Adolf Mussafia]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=tQCZU1OuBu0C&pg=PA325&lpg=PA325&dq=%22Tobler-Mussafia%22&source=bl&ots=hfQ7KgY9ae&sig=nlTlZv3lwyY1vUKHgSqgoNt3ysg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjKlIro-8rRAhUR3YMKHXQ_Bkw4ChDoAQgdMAI#v=onepage&q=%22Tobler-Mussafia%22&f=false Clause Structure and Language Change] by Adrian Battye, Ian G. Roberts</ref>
== Published works == Among his better written efforts was the five-volume ''Vermischte Beiträge zur französischen Grammatik'' ("Miscellaneous contributions to French grammar"; 1886–1912). His creation of an [[Old French]] dictionary was unfinished at the time of his death, being posthumously edited and published by [[Erhard Lommatzsch]] ("Tobler-Lommatzsch", ''Altfranzösisches wörterbuch''; 11 volumes).<ref name=HU/><ref name=HA>[https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Search/Home?lookfor=%22Tobler,Adolf,1835-1910.%22&type=author&inst= HathiTrust Digital Library] (published works)</ref> Other noted works by Tobler include: * ''Gedichte von Jehan de Condet nach der casanatensischen Handschrift'', 1860 &ndash; Poems by Jean de Condé according to the [[Biblioteca Casanatense|Casanatensian]] manuscript. * ''Aus der Chanson de geste von Auberi nach einer vaticanischen Handschrift'', 1870 &ndash; From the ''[[Chanson de geste]]'' of Auberi, according to a Vatican manuscript. * ''Li dis dou vrai aniel. Die Parabel von dem ächten Ringe, Französische Dichtung des dreizehnten Jahrhunderts'', 1871 &ndash; ''Li dis dou vrai aniel''. The parable of the true ring, French poetry of the 13th century. * ''Vom französischen Versbau alter und neuer Zeit. Zusammenstellung der Anfangsgründe'', 1880 &ndash; On French versification of old and modern times.<ref name=HA/>
